04924nam a22008055i 9780813550725DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20112011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135507257 a10.36019/97808135507252doi  a(DE-B1597)530365  a(OCoLC)805071428  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN1998.2b.F5585 2011eb 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4302/80922aB22200aFlickers of Desire :bMovie Stars of the 1910s /cJennifer M. Bean. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b48  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStar Decades: American Culture/American00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction: Stardom in the 1910s -- t1. G. M.Anderson: "Broncho Billy" among the Early "Picture Personalities" -- t2. Mary Pickford: Icon of Stardom -- t3. Lillian Gish: Clean, and White, and Pure as the Lily -- t4. Sessue Hayakawa:The Mirror, the Racialized Body, and Photogénie -- t5. Theda Bara: Orientalism, Sexual Anarchy, and the Jewish Star -- t6. Geraldine Farrar: A Star from Another Medium -- t7. George Beban: Character of the Picturesque -- t8. Pearl White and Grace Cunard:The Serial Queen's Volatile Present -- t9. Roscoe "Fatty" Arbuckle: Comedy's Starring Scapegoat -- t10. Douglas Fairbanks: Icon of Americanism -- t11. Charles Chaplin:The Object Life of Mass Culture -- tIn the Wings -- tWorks Cited -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday, we are so accustomed to consuming the amplified lives of film stars that the origins of the phenomenon may seem inevitable in retrospect. But the conjunction of the terms "movie" and "star" was inconceivable prior to the 1910s. Flickers of Desire explores the emergence of this mass cultural phenomenon, asking how and why a cinema that did not even run screen credits developed so quickly into a venue in which performers became the American film industry's most lucrative mode of product individuation. Contributors chart the rise of American cinema's first galaxy of stars through a variety of archival sources--newspaper columns, popular journals, fan magazines, cartoons, dolls, postcards, scrapbooks, personal letters, limericks, and dances. The iconic status of Charlie Chaplin's little tramp, Mary Pickford's golden curls, Pearl White's daring stunts, or Sessue Hayakawa's expressionless mask reflect the wild diversity of a public's desired ideals, while Theda Bara's seductive turn as the embodiment of feminine evil, George Beban's performance as a sympathetic Italian immigrant, or G. M. Anderson's creation of the heroic cowboy/outlaw character transformed the fantasies that shaped American filmmaking and its vital role in society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aMotion picture actors and actresseszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aAbel, Richard1 aBean, Jennifer M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBertellini, Giorgio1 aCooper, Mark1 aCurtis, Scott1 aGledhill, Christine1 aGrant, Kristen1 aKing, Rob1 aMiyao, Daisuke1 aMorey, Anne1 aStudlar, Gaylyn1 aWhissel, Kristen08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813550725423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813550725.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  